Why is this code not working for the test case given above?

The reason your code is not working for the given test case is that the number generated by concatenating all the digits in the vector is too large to fit into an `unsigned long long` variable. For example, the number formed from the given vector `[7,2,8,5,0,9,1,2,9,5,3,6,6,7,3,2,8,4,3,7,9,5,7,7,4,7,4,9,4,7,0,1,1,1,7,4,0,0,6]` is very large and is likely to cause an overflow.

One way to avoid this is to perform the "plus one" operation directly on the array/vector without converting it to a number. Here's how:

1. Start from the last digit and move toward the first digit, propagating any carry.
2. If the last digit is less than 9, just increment it and you are done.
3. If the last digit is 9, make it zero and propagate a carry to the previous digit.
4. If the first digit ends up being zero with a carry, you'll need to insert a new '1' at the beginning.

Here is some sample code to demonstrate:


#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
using namespace std;

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> plusOne(vector<int>& digits) {
        int n = digits.size();
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
            if (digits[i] < 9) {
                ++digits[i];
                return digits;
            }
            digits[i] = 0;
        }
        // If all the digits were 9, then we'll reach this point and we need to add a new '1' at the beginning.
        digits.insert(digits.begin(), 1);
        return digits;
    }
};


This approach has a time complexity of \( O(n) \) and doesn't use any additional space (except for the returned result), i.e., it has a space complexity of \( O(1) \).

