**If you don't have a rought idea or understand the code below, please check out tadasant's post for explanation by searching tadasant in discuss section.**

This post is for people who love to use {} instead of new Map() when needing a map like me.

Recently after reading this article: https://medium.com/front-end-weekly/es6-map-vs-object-what-and-when-b80621932373 , I decided to do a performance test myself on this problem.

Since leetcode has smaller amount of test cases, the run time beat % does not always mean the solution is optimal, you still have to think about run time complexity of your solution + any builtin function you used and data structure optimization.

**NOTE:**
I'm new to performance testing and only did it on http://jsben.ch/ on chrome, please comment if you got something to offer or correct about my post.

## Tests
**On LeetCode:** my solution with map was slower than obj with 37 test cases.
**On JSBEN: *code block 1* being obj {}, *code block 2* being new Map(), tests are [[nominator,denominator]......]**

**1 test case [2,1] run 2000 times:** obj is only faster sometimes than map and not by much
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/allanhsu8/image_1565868374.png)

With more tests cases it becomes apparent.


**[[1,2],[2,1],[1,998001],[-2147483648,1]] run 2000 times**
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/allanhsu8/image_1565868996.png)

Lastly, to add more random test cases and at the same time not make the tab stop responding. I used the snippet here to generate 1 random test case and push it in.
```
//This block gets run 2000 times, to not explode I add onl 1 random element at the end.
const tests = [[1,2],[2,1],[1,998001],[-2147483648,1]];


const INT_MAX = Math.pow(2,32) - 1;
const INT_MIN = -Math.pow(2,32);
const range = INT_MAX-INT_MIN;
tests.push(Math.floor(Math.random()*(range)+INT_MIN),
           Math.floor(Math.random()*(range)+INT_MIN));
```
**[[1,2],[2,1],[1,998001],[-2147483648,1],[?,?]] run 2000 times**
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/allanhsu8/image_1565869329.png)
We can see map just beats object always. **Therefore use new Map() when you are using maps!** 

For details of my code on JSBEN: http://jsben.ch/YeH2E , there are also plenty of map vs object tests on JSBEN you can search up and see for yourself of the getters and setters. Map is an object, but object is not a map.

