# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
1. The function takes two parameters: numerator and denominator, representing the fraction to be converted.

2. The code first checks if the numerator is zero. If it is, it returns "0" as the decimal representation of the fraction.

3. A variable named result is initialized as an empty string. This variable will store the decimal representation of the fraction.

4. The code handles the sign of the resulting decimal by checking if the signs of the numerator and denominator are the same. If they are not, a "-" sign is added to the result.

5. The numerator and denominator are converted to their absolute values using the Math.abs() function. This ensures that the calculations are performed correctly regardless of the sign.

6. The integer part of the fraction is determined by dividing the absolute numerator by the absolute denominator and using Math.floor() to round down the division result. The integer part is added to the result.

7. The code calculates the remainder of the division using the modulus operator (%). If the remainder is zero, it means there is no fractional part, so the result is returned.

8. If there is a fractional part, a decimal point is added to the result.

9. The code uses a Map called map to track the remainders and their positions. This is done to detect repeating patterns in the decimal representation of the fraction.

10. The code enters a loop that continues until the remainder becomes zero. In each iteration, it checks if the remainder is already in the map. If it is, it means a repeating pattern is detected. The code retrieves the position of the previous occurrence of the remainder and adds parentheses around the repeating pattern in the result.

11. If the remainder is not in the map, it is added to the map with its current position.

12. The remainder is then multiplied by 10 and divided by the denominator. The floor value of this division is added to the result.

13. The remainder is updated by taking the modulus of the division result with the denominator.

14. Once the loop ends, the final result is returned.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(denominator)
where the denominator represents the size of the input denominator. This is because the loop iterates until the remainder becomes zero, and in the worst case, the remainder can take values from 1 to the denominator.

- Space complexity:
 O(denominator)
as the map can store up to denominator number of entries in the worst case scenario where there is a repeating pattern of length denominator.

