solutions.content:
Calculation of the Integral part is simple. Its basic division. 
After that we need to multply the remainder by 10 and make it the new numerator and keep calculating the decimal part.
We will save the states of the numerator and if the states get repeated again, this would mean that we have recurring part. Then we can just insert are brackets around the recurring part.

Its basically the division algorithm with just a hashmap to check if there exists a recurrence in the fractional part of the number.

```
class Solution {
    HashMap<Long, Integer> visited = new HashMap<>(); 
    // Stores states(numerators) and indices where the '(' would come if this is the state that starts the recurrence.

    public String fractionToDecimal(int numerator, int denominator) {
        long n = numerator;
        long d = denominator;
        boolean negative = false;

		// We calculate the answer as positive numbers and then add the signs at the end.
        if(n < 0){
            n*=-1;
            negative = true;
        }
        if(d < 0){
            d*=-1;
            negative = !negative;
        }

        String sign = "";

        if(negative && n != 0){
            sign ="-";
        }

		//Preprocessing. We get the part before the decimal first. Then check if there exists a remainder.
		// Only then do we preoceed ahead with the fractional part.

        long q = n/d;
        long r = n%d;
        StringBuilder str = new StringBuilder(sign);
        str.append(q);
        if(r == 0){
            return str.toString();
        }
        str.append('.');
        n = 10 * r;
        while(n > 0){
            if(visited.containsKey(n)){
                str.append(')');
                break;
            }
            visited.put(n, str.length());
            q = n/d;
            r = n %d;
            str.append(q);
            n = 10 * r;
        }
        if(visited.containsKey(n)){
            str.insert(visited.get(n), "(");
        }
        return str.toString();
    }
}
```

