## **Approach 1:** Preprocessing using Dynamic Programming
1. str1=[s1,n1] and str2=[s2,n2], we need to find how many times the string str2  occurs as distinct subsequences in the string str1.
2. Let cnt1 and cnt2 be the number of times we have visited the string s1 and the string s2.
3. We also maintain pointers i, and j to iterate over s1 and s2. 
4. In the brute force approach, we scan s1 and s2 and increments all these variables accordingly. The required result is obtained by cnt2/n2. But the time complexity is O(s1.size()*n1).
5. As the string str1 is the repetition of string s1, we can improve the brute force with some preprocessing. 
6. Let us the define the state **dp[i][j]=maxMatch**, such that maxMatch is the maximum length of s2[j:]+[s2,x], x>0, which occurs as subsequence in the string s1[i:].
7. Now, we can use this pre-processing to fast-forward our brute force approach. We can process the entire string s1, in O(1) time. The overall time complexity of this approach will be O(n1).
8. We no longer require the pointer i for string s1 as the entire string will be processed in O(1)  time. We just need to carefully increment the pointer j and cnt2.
9. While calculating the result, we will only require dp[0][j] states but not other states so therefore we can bring down the space complexity from O(s1.size()*s2.size()) to O(s2.size())
10. Therefore the space complexity is **O(s2.size())** and the time complexity is **O(n1+s1.size()*s2.size())**.
11. Calculating the actual result from this preprocessing is quite simple, we just iterate over the string s1 for n1 times and increment the pointer j and cnt2 pointers accordingly.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int getMaxRepetitions(string s1, int n1, string s2, int n2) {
        vector<int>dp(s2.size());
        for(int i=s1.size()-1 ; i>=0 ; i--)
        { vector<int>tmp(s2.size());
          for(int j=s2.size()-1 ; j>=0 ; j--)
          { if(s1[i]==s2[j])
            { tmp[j]++;
              if((i+1)<s1.size())
              { int p=j+1; if(p==s2.size()) p=0;
                tmp[j]+=dp[p];
              }
            }
            else if((i+1)<s1.size())
              tmp[j]=dp[j];
          }  
          dp=tmp;
        }

        int res=0,cnt1=0,cnt2=0,j=0;
        while(cnt1<n1)
        { int maxMatch=dp[j];
          cnt1++;

          int diff=s2.size()-j;
          if(diff>=maxMatch)
          { j+=maxMatch;
            if(j==s2.size()) { j=0; cnt2++; }
          }
          else 
          { cnt2++;
            maxMatch-=diff; j=maxMatch%s2.size();
            cnt2+=(maxMatch/(s2.size()));
          }
        }
        return cnt2/n2;
    }
};

```

## **Approach 2: Finding the Pattern**

1. In the brute force approach, we iterate over s1 for n1 times. Whenever we are at index 0 of s1, the maximum **number of different possible indexes pointing to s2 is s2.size()**. Therefore, by pigeonhole principle, if we visit the string s1 at (s1.size()+1)^{th} time (in the worst case), we will be visiting a particular index at the second time.
2. Note: In the previous approach as well, we were maintaining the j^{th} index, pointing to s2, for each iteration of s1.
2. Therefore, the pattern had occurred for the first time. Using this pattern, we can now calculate our required result in O(1) time.
3. Suppose, the index ind pointing to s2 occurs at i^{th}  and k^{th} iteration of s2, where k<i. Then the next occurrence of index ind occurs at [i+(i-k)]^{th} iteration and so on. We must have, i+t*(i-k)<n1 [using 0 based indexed while iterating through the string s1] ⇒ i+t*(i-k) <= (n1-1) ⇒ **t <= (n1-1-i)/(i-k)** and therefore the pattern occurs for t+1, times.
4. Then the maximum iteration number we can achieve for the occurrence of pattern is: maxind=i+t*(i-k).
5. Our result can be obtained in three parts:
First part: **res+=cnt[k]** (Before occurrence of pattern).
Second part: **res+=(cnt[i]-cnt[k])\*(t+1)** [The pattern itself]
Third part: **res+=cnt[k+n1-1-maxind]-cnt[k]**   [The remaining part]
6. The Time Complexity is O(s1.size()*s2.size()) and Space Complexity is O(s2.size()).

```
class Solution {
public:
    int getMaxRepetitions(string s1, int n1, string s2, int n2) {
        vector<int>nxtind(s2.size()+1),cnt(s2.size()+1);
        int ind=0,tcnt=0;

        for(int i=0; i<n1 ; i++)
        { for(int j=0 ; j<s1.size(); j++)
          { if(s1[j]==s2[ind]) ind++;
            if(ind==s2.size()) {ind=0; tcnt++;}   
          }
          cnt[i]=tcnt;
          nxtind[i]=ind;
          for(int k=0 ; k<i ; k++)
          { if(nxtind[k]==ind)
            { int res=cnt[k];
              int t=(n1-1-i)/(i-k);
              res+=(cnt[i]-cnt[k])*(t+1); 
              int maxind=i+(i-k)*t;
              if(maxind<(n1-1)) res+=cnt[k+n1-1-maxind]-cnt[k];
              return res/n2;
            }  
          }
        }
        return cnt[n1-1]/n2;
    }
};
```

