solutions.content:
Nice warm up for the week, this is a nice problem to solve in one simple go.

First of all, we are going create a few support variables:
* `mr` and `mc` will store the number of rows and columns in the provided matrix;
* `nx` and `ny` are 2 pointers we will use with our newly created array.

We will then check if the calls we are getting is either illegal (ie: the total number of elements in the new matrix does not match) or if the provided coordinates are identical to the existing one - in either case returning `mat`.

If that is not the case, we will then create another variable, `res`, a vector of vectors of `r` rows and `c` columns.

Next, we will populate `res` looping with `cy` and `cx` through `mat` and:
* assigning the currently pointed value (`mat[cy][cx]`) to the matching cell in the new matrix (`res[ny][nx++]`);
* advance `ny` and reset `nx` to `0` every time we reach the end of the row in the `res` (ie: `nx == c`).

Once done, we can return `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> matrixReshape(vector<vector<int>>& mat, int r, int c) {
        // support variables
        int mr = mat.size(), mc = mat[0].size(), nx = 0, ny = 0;
        // detecting illegal calls and when the new matrix has the same size
        if (mr * mc != r * c || mr == r && mc == c) return mat;
        vector<vector<int>> res(r, vector<int>(c));
        // populating ress
        for (int cy = 0; cy < mr; cy++) {
            for (int cx = 0; cx < mc; cx++) {
                res[ny][nx++] = mat[cy][cx];
                // updating nx and ny when we reached the end of a row
                if (nx == c) nx = 0, ny++;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

