solutions.content:
Suppose n = 6, k = 4
We will form array as :
arr[0] = 1,
arr[1] = 1 + k(=4) = 5, and k--,
arr[2] =  5 - k(=3) = 2, and k--,
arr[3] = 2 + k(=2)= 4,  and k--,
arr[4] = 4 - k(=1) = 3, and k-- (Here k = 0) after this we will fill remaining numbers normally
arr[5] = 6
So array formed : [1, 5, 2, 4, 3, 6] after following operation it will be [4, 3, 2, 1, 3] which contains exactly 4 distinct numbers.
```
class Solution {
    public int[] constructArray(int n, int k) {
        int[] arr = new int[n];
        arr[0] = 1;
        int x = 1 + k;
        for(int i=1 ; i<arr.length ; i++){
            arr[i] = (k <= 0) ? ++x : (i % 2 == 0) ? arr[i-1] - k : arr[i-1] + k;
            k--;
        }
        return arr;
    }
}
```
Time Complexity : O(n)
Auxiliary Space : O(1)
