1. Arrange first k+1 elements to obtain k different distinct numbers:
	  ex. For (k = 5, n = 9) the first 6 numbers will be: [1, 6, 2, 5, 3, 4]. This will result in 5 distinct integers: [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]
2. For the rest of them (from k+1 to n), we can just add them to the result in increasing order which will give us 1 all the way.
3. The final result will be for k=5, n=9 : [1, 6, 2, 5, 3, 4, 7, 8, 9]

```
class Solution {
    public int[] constructArray(int n, int k) {
        int[] result = new int[n];

        int index = 0;
        int x = 1, y = k+1;

        while (x <= y) {
            result[index++] = x++;

            if (x < y) {
                result[index++] = y--;
            }
        }

        for (int i=index+1; i<=n; i++) {
            result[index++] = i;
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

