solutions.content:
1. If the integer array ranging from ```1``` to ```n```, the max possible diffenece is ```n-1```. 
	That is, ```ans = [1, n, 2, n-1, ..., n/2]```.
2. If we only want the result has exactly ```k``` distinct integer, the easiest way is to 
	(1) Create an array from ```1``` to ```k+1``` which has max diffenece. 
	(2) Attach the remaining numbers from ```k+2``` to ```n``` in the end of the result.
	That is, ```ans = [1, k+1, 2, k, ..., k/2+1] + [k+2, k+3, ..., n]```.

```
    public int[] constructArray(int n, int k) {
        int[] ans = new int[n];
        // Create an array from 1 to n
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) ans[i] = i+1;
        // Let the first k+1 element has the max difference
        for(int i = 0, j = 0; i <= k; j++) {
            ans[i++] = j+1;
            if(i <= k) ans[i++] = k-j+1;
        }
        return ans;
    }
```
Time: O(n)

