# Intuition
We need to create an answer array `[a1, a2, a3, ... , an]` ranged from `1` to `n`, that satisfies the criteria `[|a1 - a2|, |a2 - a3|, ... , |an-1 - an|]` have distinct `k` elements.

So when `k = 1`, the difference between adjacent elements must be `1`

And when `k = 2`, the difference between adjacent elements must be `1` or `2`, and both must occure at least once

And when `k = 3`, the difference between adjacent elements must be `1`, `2` or `3`, and all must occure at least once

And so on...

So we will use the `k` to fulfill our requirement first, then fill the rest of the array ascendingly till we reach `n`.

# Approach
Assume `n = 10` and `k = 3`
We will fill `n` as follow:
`[1, 1 + k]` k = 3
`[1, 4, 4 - (k - 1)]` k = -2
`[1, 4, 2, 2 + (k - 2)]` k = 1
`[1, 4, 2, 3]`

Notice how `k` updates; the value reduces by one, and the sign changes.

We have fulfilled the requirement, now fill the array normally using:
`answer[i] = i + 1`

`[1, 4, 2, 3, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10]`

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public int[] ConstructArray(int n, int k) {
        int[] answer = new int[n];
        answer[0] = 1;

        int i = 1;
        while(k != 0)
        {
            answer[i] = answer[i - 1] + k;
            i++;

            k = -(k - (Math.Abs(k) / k));
        }

        while(i < n)
        {
            answer[i] = i + 1;
            i++;
        }

        return answer;
    }
}
```

