# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
There are different ways to do this problem but here is a simple way.

If we have to make k different differences then the differences should contain all numbers from 1 to k (differences can repeat but all numbers from 1 to k should be covered). For ex. if K is 3 then no matter what the array is, 1,2,3 should be the differences.

So, all we need to do is first set the starting number in array as 1. We also make a hash array to store numbers that have been covered. Now, we sub k and add k to it. If the new number is a valid number (between 1 and n) and is not in hash array then that is the next number (check first for sub and if that is not valid then add). Then subtract 1 from k. Do this till k becomes zero.

After K is 0, simply traverse the hash array and add the numbers that have not been covered in ascending order. Done!!!

I am not sure why the last step works but I think the differnce will never exceed 2 and when k is 1 it will not exceed 1. But, I can't prove it mathematically.
