# Intuition
The intuition for this problem is simple.We have given that there should be k distinct differences .So, the differences between consecutive elements will range from 1 to k i.e. 1,2,3,4....,k.
So, we have to somehow manage these differences atleast one time. And after adjusting these differences one time each,if elements from range of 1 to n left to be pushed in vector will be pushed directly,as we have managed all the distinct differences for atleast one time.


# Approach
We can approach this problem by simply pushing the largest element first then we will push (last element-k) then decremeting k,then we will push (last element+k) then decremeting k, and so on. This will help us to store distinct elements in vector with varying differences.
After this process,if elements remained to be pushed will be pushed from largest to 1 sequentially.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
Time complexity for the above solution will be O(k*k).


- Space complexity:
Space complexity will be O(n), required for storing the elements in vector.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> constructArray(int n, int k) {
        vector<int> ans; //required answer vector
        int z=k;
        ans.push_back(n); //pushing the highest element into vector
        int ct=0;
        while(k){
            //if-else conditions to execute alternate addition and subtraction from previously pushed element
           if(ct%2==0){
              ans.push_back(ans[ct]-k);
              k--; ct++;
           }
           else { 
            ans.push_back(ans[ct]+k);
            k--; ct++;
           }
        }
        //pushing the remaining elements into vector sequentially from higher to lower
        if(n-z!=1){
        for(int i=n-z-2;i>=0;i--){
            ans.push_back(i+1);
         }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

