# Step 1. Play With Certain Cases
First, lets try solving the problem for the easiest cases, k = 1 and k = n-1, the minimum and maximum possible values for k. K denotes the unique amount of "step sizes" we can use to bounce around the array and hit every number once.

There is a straight forward answer for one unique step size:
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/bd1e1c2c-afd8-46e9-8c5b-cb9160049faf_1672540759.7595036.png)

Now lets tackle the latter case, k = n - 1. Note that in this case, every step size that we make must be unique, since there are n - 1 steps in total to make. To get an idea of maybe what to do, lets see what moves we have after starting with some element as our first element in our answer:

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6745cdf8-7ea8-4b0b-878e-e4e40ea65ff8_1672540975.356649.png)

The red numbers indicate the step size to reach that number from the arrowed element. Note that starting at either the front or end provides us the nicest path forward. It provides the maximum amount of unique ways to progress, and it wont leave a random hole in the middle of the array that we can't acsess later. 

Lets choose the end (choosing the front works too, but I simply decided to go with the end). What should our next element be? Well, again it is nice to not have random holes in the middle of our array, so 4 and 1 seem like nice choices.

If you choose 4, you will notice that you will later be forced to make another step of size 1. Going from 5 to 4 was a step size of 1, so thus we repeated a step of size 1, and thus going from 5 to 4 will result in a sequence that is not a solution to this case.

So, lets now choose 1. If you continue, you may now notice the pattern at this point, we choose the end, then the first element, and then the last element left, etc in a spiral. This will produce all unique steps.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ca73df71-01b6-470a-8758-6d1e972baa6c_1672541772.1100557.png)

Notice that we take a step of 4, then 3, then 2, then 1, and at every stage, the indices that we haven't visited yet form a contiguous subarray.


# Step 2. Try To Generalize

So now, the final peice of the puzzle is how do we get the solutions where we don't need to use all unique step sizes. We know the solution to the two extremes, and this can give use a clue into how to approach this. Since the spiral approach of the k = n - 1 case always leaves a contiguous subarray unvisited at every iteration, we are always free at any point to exit the spiral stepping and go into the linear marching pattern of k = 1:

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/096cd56e-5ba2-4d45-b2d2-17ec53ee5de4_1672542289.8664255.png)

This works out really nicely, and solves our problem. Note in all cases, we do k - 1 "spiral" steps, and then we finish up the rest with marching steps.

All that is left is to implement it. The following solution has O(n) time complexity and O(n) space complexity in order to store and build the answer. 

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int[] constructArray(int n, int k) {
        int[] answer = new int[n];
        int answerIndex = 0;

        boolean useHighNum = true;
        int low = 1;
        int high = n;

        // Spiraling
        for (int i = 0; i < k - 1; i++) {
            if (useHighNum) {
                answer[answerIndex] = high;
                high--;
            } else {
                answer[answerIndex] = low;
                low++;
            }
            answerIndex++;
            useHighNum = !useHighNum;
        }

        // Marching
        if (useHighNum) {
            while (answerIndex < n) {
                answer[answerIndex] = high;
                high--;
                answerIndex++;
            }
        } else {
            while (answerIndex < n) {
                answer[answerIndex] = low;
                low++;
                answerIndex++;
            }
        }

        return answer;
    }
}
```

