When k is greater than 1, there is a simple pattern to fill the array with numbers as [ 1 , n-1, 2 , n-2, 3 , n-2....]. Now when k =1 we need constant difference between all the left numbers. |a-b| == |c-d|. For the this, the most appropriate constant difference is 1. 

For example. N=6 and k =3
till k=2 answer vector will be filled as [ 1, 6, 2 ]
for k =1. the rest elements can be filled as [1, 6, 2, 3, 4, 5]

For N=6 and k =4
till k=3 answer vector will be filled as [ 1, 6, 2, 5 ]
for k =1. the rest elements can be filled as [1, 6, 2, 5, 4,3].

So for k =1, the trick is check the last element filled. if it was filled with s (smaller number) next elements will be filled in increasing order. [......2, 3, 4, 5]
if it was filled with e (bigger number) next elements will be filled first in decreasing order till s==e and then in increasing order. [....,6, 2, 5, 4,3].

```
vector<int> constructArray(int n, int k) {
        int s=2, e=n;
        vector<int> ans(n);
        ans[0]=1;

        int i=1;
        while(i<n){
            if(k>1){
                ans[i++]=i%2==0? s++ : e--;
                k--;
            }else{
                if(ans[i-1]<s || s==e){
                    ans[i++]=s++;
                }else{
                    if(e>s){
                        ans[i++]=e--;
                    }
                }
            }
        }  
        return ans;
    }
```

