# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- Each element is placed at a minimum of 1 gap (Assume we are first filling the even positions, later you'll understand why)
- If the most occuring element cannot be placed at 1 gap (While placing the elements at even position it exceeds the size of the string) then it is not possible to get the desired string
- If the task of placing the most occuring element at, at most 1 gap is fulfilled and:
-> we have reached the end of the string then : we can place the remaining elements in any order and no consecutive elemets will be the same
-> we did not reach the end of the string then: we can place the remaining elements continuing from where we left at 1 gap until we reach the end, then we fill the odd positions one by one.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Create a map of frequencies of all the characters in the string
- Find the maximum frequency and the maximum occuring character
- Place the maximum occuring element at even positions until the remaining frequency is exhausted
- if after placing at all even positions characters are remaining then it is certainly not possible to get the desired string
- iterate through the map to get the remaining characters, and first place them at even positions if left, then start placing them at odd positions by cycling the index back to 1 if it reaches the end
- There you have the resultant string

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
-> We are going to each index of the string exactly once so O(N)
-> The map would store at max 26 characters(a-z), so traversing it is as good as constant so O(26) 
 Worst case = O(26*N) ~ O(N)

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
We are just using a map to store at most 26 characters so 
Worst case= O(26)~O(1)

