# Intuition & Approach
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- At first I thought of the priority queue or Hash table.
- But in discussion section I found that it can be done without sorting.
- Now, jump to the logic part
- First, keep track of the character having **maximum frequency**.
- If **frequency of that char is greater than the half the size of the given string**, then it's impossible.
- To organize the string so that no adjacent element would be same,
-  We need to understand that the char having maximum frequency should arrange in alternative fashion.(**simple arranging k elements in n space so that no adjacent are same**).
- After that the char having second largest frequency should be filled **if the resultant string size is still less than the given string**.
-------------------------
- Create a vector to store frequency of character
- Keep track of the char having max freq, and check base case(impossible to reorganize).
- Now, put the characters alternatively
- At last return answer.
---
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(s.size())
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1) : Because the vector of size 26 is constant.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
---
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string reorganizeString(string s) {
        vector<int> cnt(26);
        int mostFreq =0, i=0;

        for(char c: s){
            if(++cnt[c-'a'] > cnt[mostFreq]) mostFreq = (c-'a');
        }
        if(2*cnt[mostFreq]-1 > s.size()) return "";

        while(cnt[mostFreq]){
            s[i] = ('a' + mostFreq);
            cnt[mostFreq]--;
            i+=2;
        }

        for(int j=0; j<26; j++){
            while(cnt[j]){
                if(i >= s.size()) i=1;
                s[i] = ('a' + j);
                cnt[j]--;
                i+=2;
            }
        }

        return s;
    } 
};
```

