solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem requires rearranging the characters in a string so that no two adjacent characters are the same. One way to approach this is to prioritize the characters based on their frequencies and try to place the most frequent characters apart from each other. Using a max-heap (priority queue) allows us to efficiently process and place characters with higher frequencies first.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. First, we count the frequency of each character in the input string s.

1. We create a max-heap (priority queue) and enqueue each character along with its frequency.

1. While the max-heap is not empty:
a. Dequeue the character with the highest frequency.
b. Append the character to the result string.
c. If the previously dequeued character's frequency is greater than 0, enqueue it again.
d. Decrement the frequency of the currently dequeued character.

1. If the length of the result string matches the length of the input string, we have successfully rearranged the characters. Otherwise, it's not possible to rearrange the characters to meet the requirement.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Let n be the length of the input string s.

- Counting character frequencies takes O(n) time.
- Enqueuing all characters into the max-heap takes O(26 * log n) time in the worst case (where 26 is the number of lowercase English letters), which simplifies to O(log n) since constants are dropped.
- The loop that dequeues characters runs at most n times, and each dequeue operation takes O(log n) time.
- Constructing the result string from characters takes O(n) time.
- Overall, the time complexity is dominated by the max-heap operations and is approximately O(n * log n).

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
- We use an array charCount to store character frequencies, which takes O(26) = O(1) space.
- The max-heap can hold at most 26 characters, which results in O(26) = O(1) space.
- The result string takes O(n) space.
- The custom PriorityQueue implementation uses a list to store the heap, which also takes O(n) space.
Overall, the space complexity is O(n).

# Code
```
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Text;

public class Solution {
    public string ReorganizeString(string s) {
        int n = s.Length;
        int[] charCount = new int[26];
        foreach (char c in s) {
            charCount[c - 'a']++;
        }

        PriorityQueue<(char, int)> maxHeap = new PriorityQueue<(char, int)>((a, b) => b.Item2.CompareTo(a.Item2));
        for (char c = 'a'; c <= 'z'; c++) {
            if (charCount[c - 'a'] > 0) {
                maxHeap.Enqueue((c, charCount[c - 'a']));
            }
        }

        StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();
        (char, int) prev = ('#', -1);

        while (maxHeap.Count > 0) {
            var current = maxHeap.Dequeue();
            result.Append(current.Item1);

            if (prev.Item2 > 0) {
                maxHeap.Enqueue(prev);
            }

            current.Item2--;
            prev = current;
        }

        if (n == result.Length) {
            return result.ToString();
        }

        return "";
    }
}

public class PriorityQueue<T> {
    private List<T> heap;
    private Comparison<T> comparison;

    public int Count { get { return heap.Count; } }

    public PriorityQueue(Comparison<T> comparison) {
        this.heap = new List<T>();
        this.comparison = comparison;
    }

    public void Enqueue(T item) {
        heap.Add(item);
        int currentIndex = heap.Count - 1;

        while (currentIndex > 0) {
            int parentIndex = (currentIndex - 1) / 2;
            if (comparison(heap[parentIndex], heap[currentIndex]) <= 0) {
                break;
            }

            T tmp = heap[parentIndex];
            heap[parentIndex] = heap[currentIndex];
            heap[currentIndex] = tmp;

            currentIndex = parentIndex;
        }
    }

    public T Dequeue() {
        if (heap.Count == 0) {
            throw new InvalidOperationException("PriorityQueue is empty.");
        }

        T result = heap[0];
        heap[0] = heap[heap.Count - 1];
        heap.RemoveAt(heap.Count - 1);

        int currentIndex = 0;
        while (true) {
            int leftChildIndex = 2 * currentIndex + 1;
            int rightChildIndex = 2 * currentIndex + 2;
            int smallestChildIndex = currentIndex;

            if (leftChildIndex < heap.Count && comparison(heap[leftChildIndex], heap[smallestChildIndex]) < 0) {
                smallestChildIndex = leftChildIndex;
            }

            if (rightChildIndex < heap.Count && comparison(heap[rightChildIndex], heap[smallestChildIndex]) < 0) {
                smallestChildIndex = rightChildIndex;
            }

            if (smallestChildIndex == currentIndex) {
                break;
            }

            T tmp = heap[currentIndex];
            heap[currentIndex] = heap[smallestChildIndex];
            heap[smallestChildIndex] = tmp;

            currentIndex = smallestChildIndex;
        }

        return result;
    }
}

```

