solutions.content:
Good for you if you're a genius who came up with the pq solution first try.

If you've never seen this question b4, it might make sense to use DFS + backtracking to find all possibilities, and return a valid string:

```
class Solution {
    public String reorganizeString(String S) {

        HashSet<String> v = new HashSet<>(); //visited set

        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(S);

        //dfs all possibilities, use backtrack to make candidates

        //if found, just return that possibility

        return dfs(sb, v);

    }

    private String dfs(StringBuilder sb, HashSet<String> v) {

        String curr = sb.toString();

        //base case, no adjacents
        if(!adjacent(curr)) return curr;

        if(v.contains(curr)) return "";

        v.add(curr);

        //swap all possibilites
        for(int i = 0; i < curr.length()-1; i++) {

            //swap
            swap(sb, i, i+1);

            //send out dfs
            String res = dfs(sb, v);
            if (res != "") return res;

            //swap back
            swap(sb,i,i+1);
        }

        return "";

    }


    private boolean adjacent(String curr) {

        for(int i = 0; i < curr.length()-1; i++) {
            if(curr.charAt(i)==curr.charAt(i+1)) return true;
        }

        return false;
    }

    //swaps char at i and j
    private void swap(StringBuilder sb, int i, int j) {

        char c1 = sb.charAt(i);
        sb.replace(i,i+1, ""+sb.charAt(i+1));
        sb.replace(i+1, i+2, ""+c1);

    }
}
```

Unfortunately this gets TLE (though it passes many smaller test cases). Why is that?

Well your branching factor is O(n), and the number of levels in your recursion tree (i.e. the number of swaps necessary to get a valid string) is *at least* O(n), but likely worse. So you're already dealing with an O(n^n) complexity, but it's probably worse. 

To improve the time complexity, you have to ask yourself: perhaps there is some way to directly solve this problem without generating a tree of all the possibilities. 

Indeed there is: consider "aab".

How do you know you can sucessfully re-org this string? 

You can lay out the "a_a" and use "b" as a "resource" to stop the adjacency.

Ok, but would this work with more complicated examples? S = "aaabbcccc"

Let's start by laying out the c's: "c_c_c_c"

We need 3 "resources" to stop the adjacency. Ok let's just use "a" then:

"cacacac". Uh oh, now we're stuck with the two b's...

At this point, you should realize that the "resources" need to be dynamically updated and chosen. That is to say, instead of just choosing to use the 3 a's from the get-go, use two a's, realize now that you have more b resources, so start using the b resources.

Naturally, dynamically updating and using the highest resource char should get you thinking of a PQ.

Let's see if it works:

"c_c_c_c" -> "cacac_c" -> "cacacbc" -> "cacacbc" + "ab"

Nice.

```
 public String reorganizeString(String S) {

        //char buckets
        int[] cfreq = new int[26];
        for(char c: S.toCharArray()) cfreq[c-'a']++;

        PriorityQueue<Character> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((c1, c2)->{
            return cfreq[c2-'a'] - cfreq[c1-'a'];
        });

        for(int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
            if(cfreq[i]>0) pq.add((char)(i+'a'));
        }

        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();//builds res

        //we choose largest char bucket as a "base", poll from pq
        while(!pq.isEmpty()) {

            //try to fill in with other chars, use a "resource" pq which organizes char bucket by resources remaining
            char base = pq.poll();
            int needFill = cfreq[base-'a']-1;

             //start making nonadjacent string
            sb.append(base);

            if(needFill==0) continue; //we're good, nothing to fill in b/c single char

            while(needFill>0) {

                if(pq.isEmpty()) return ""; //couldn't fill in everything

                //use a resource, make sure put back in pq to properly update
                char resource = pq.poll(); //resource character
                cfreq[resource-'a']--;

                if(cfreq[resource-'a'] > 0) pq.add(resource); //only add it back if have resource remaining

                //will be non-adjacent
                sb.append(resource);
                sb.append(base);

                needFill--;
            }

            //repeat on next largest char bucket remaining

        }

        return sb.toString();

    }

```

