# Intuition
The intuition behind this algorithm was that we can split a string into similar segments that later need to fill with different characters.

# Approach
The approach is to count the occurences of each character in the string s. Then, we select the one with the most occurences, and if it is occuring too much (max > sum + 1), that means that there will be at least one segment that will be empty (eg. aab resolves to ab|a, but
aaab resolves to ab|a|a). Then, we add next elements to the result,
and every time we do that we add the character thathas the most remaining occurences, wasn't the last added character and isn't the most occuring char itself. And that's it.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(26n) ~ O(n): for each character in s we loop through the array of length 26 (length of the alphabet).

- Space complexity:
O(n): we need a variable result that will store our result of length s.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public String reorganizeString(String s) {
        //edge cases
        if(s.equals("")){return "";}
        else if(s.length() == 1){return s;}

        //Table used to count the number 
        //of occurences for each character
        int[] chars = new int[26];
        //Filling up the table
        for(int i = 0; i < s.length(); ++i)
        {++chars[s.charAt(i) - 97];}

        //Finding the cahacter with most occurences
        int max = 0;
        int sum = 0;
        int maxIter = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < chars.length; ++i){
            if(chars[i] > max){
                sum += max;
                maxIter = i;
                max = chars[i];
            }
            else{sum += chars[i];}
        }
        //If the number of occurences of the "max" character
        //is greater than sum+1, it means that at least two
        //occurences of this character would be adjacent,
        //so we return "".
        if(max > sum && max - sum >= 2){return "";}
        int iter = 0;
        //StringBuilder is mutable, so it is more
        //memory-efficient than the String class itself.
        StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();
        int amount = s.length()/max;
        //Edge case, eg if we have "aaaabbbb", amount is 2,
        //but we want to add only one character ('b') after 'a'.
        if(amount * max == s.length()){--amount;}
        int subMax = max;
        //We iterate as long as our result is shorter
        //than the given String s
        while(result.length() < s.length()){
            //Appending the character that occurs the most in s
            result.append((char)(97+maxIter));
            iter = maxIter;
            for(int i = 0; i < amount; ++i){
                if(result.length() >= s.length()){break;}
                //Looking for the most frequently appearing
                //character that wasn't appended to the result
                //and is not our "max" character.
                int maxLocal = 0;
                int maxIterLocal = 0;
                for(int j = 0; j < chars.length; ++j){
                    if(chars[j] > maxLocal && 
                    j != iter && j != maxIter){
                        maxLocal = chars[j];
                        maxIterLocal = j;
                    }
                }
                iter = maxIterLocal;
                //If we didn't find any character other than
                //our "max" char and the char that was added last,
                //we continue our loop.
                if(iter == 0 && chars[iter] == 0){continue;}
                result.append((char)(97+(iter%26)));
                --chars[iter%26];
            }
        }

        return result.toString();
    }
}
```

