# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Since we have to check if adjacent characters are same or not, we can use two pointers to solve this problem. Using two pointers, we can check if adjacent characters are same. One pointer will check if **adjacent characters** are **same** and the other will **fetch new characters** incase adjacent characters are same.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

Intialise two pointers `i = 1, j = 1` for comparsion from the first index of the string.

**i pointer** will be used for checking if adjacent characters are equal.
**j pointer** will be used for fetching new characters if adjacent characters are equal.

There can be two cases. 

1. **The adjacent characters are not equal**, i.e `s[i] != s[i - 1]`. In this case, we can simply move both of our pointers forward, i.e `i++, j++`.
2. **The adjacent characters are equal**, i.e `s[i] == s[i - 1]`. In this case, we utilize our `j pointer` to search for an index such that `s[j] != s[i]`. Once we find such an index, we swap the characters i.e, `swap(s[i], s[j])`. Now increase i pointer by 2, i.e `i += 2.`

*Do a dry run on the given testcases using this logic. ^_^*

## Edge Cases 
In step 2, there is a possibility that we don't find an *index to swap with using our j pointer*. However, it does not necessarily mean that a correct string does not exist.

Consider this testcase:

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/aca096e2-adaa-45c4-8e94-a414c10a64d9_1692769219.832241.png)

#### 1st iteration 
    i = 1, j = 1. s[i] != s[i - 1]. Therefore i and j increase by 1.

#### 2nd iteration
    i = 2, j = 2. s[i] == s[i - 1]. j now increases to 3. swap(s[i], s[j]). i += 2 => i = 4.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/07a5567e-f513-4e69-bce8-ba2a14e2729b_1692769563.5914683.png)

*current state*

#### 3rd iteration
    i = 4, j = 3. s[i] == s[i - 1]. j now exceeds the size of string s.

If we now conclude that there a correct string does not exist, then our conclusion would be wrong. Therefore, we need to traverse the string once again from the **opposite direction** using the same logic as discussed above. Introducing this correction would solve the above edge case.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string reorganizeString(string s) {
        int n = s.length(), i = 1, j = 1;
        if(n == 1) //We have to deal with this edge case separately
        {
            return s;
        }
        //Traversing the string from the front.
        while(i < n && j < n)
        {
            if(s[i] == s[i - 1])// if adjacent characters are equal
            {
                while(j < n && s[i] == s[j])
                {
                    j++;//Increase j until we come across a character that is different from the character at index i
                }
                if(j >= n)
                {
                    break;
                }
                swap(s[i], s[j]);
                i += 2;
            }
            else
            {
                i++, j++;
            }
        }
        i = n - 2, j = n - 2;
        //Traversing from the end to deal with edge cases
        //Notice that the exact same logic has been used in both traversals.
        while(i >= 0 && j >= 0)
        {
            if(s[i] == s[i + 1])
            {
                while(j >= 0 && s[i] == s[j])
                {
                    j--;
                }
                if(j < 0)
                {
                    return "";// We are now certain that a correct string does not exist.
                }
                swap(s[i], s[j]);
                i -= 2;
            }
            else
            {
                i--, j--;
            }
        }
        return s;
    }
};
```

